@node graphic_prefs "Graphic Preferences"

@{b}Trees@{ub}

Shall trees be drawn in the landscape? 

@{b}Flag Animation@{ub}

Shall  the  flag  move?  If not, only after the wind changes a new picture is
drawn (on a slow computer (e.g. A500) it is better to turn off the animation,
because it uses to much calculation time and the whole game runs very slow).

@{b}Shake Screen@{ub}

Shall  the  screen  shake when hit (or a miss strikes in the near vicinity of
the cannon)?

@{b}Balloon@{ub}

Here can switch the balloon on or off.

@{b}Rabbit@{ub}

Here can switch the rabbit on or off.

@{b}Soldiers@{ub}

Here can switch the soldiers on or off.

@{b}Landscape@{ub}

With  this  slider  gadget  you  can  select the appearance of the landscape.
'Flat' means  a  really  flat  landscape,  while  'Rough' means a mountainous
landscape. (This setting is first used when a new landscape is generated).

@{b}Ground Draw@{ub}

With  this  slider  you can select the speed with which the landscape and the
trees are drawn. (Some people like it, if the landscape is drawn slowly, like
it  was on the C-64 :-) [If the slider is on the right the landscape is drawn
as fast as possible, without a delay]).

@{b}Shoot Speed@{ub}

Here you can change the speed of the weapons (don't make it too slow, because
it then looks very unrealistic).

@{b}Background Directory@{ub}

The directory in which the backgrounds are. Only change this if you know what
you  do! New or changed backgrounds can be saved into this directory. After a
new start of the game they are used too.

@{b}Background Load@{ub}

In which order shall the landscapes be loaded? 'Random Order' means at random
while 'In Order' means one after the other.

@endnode


@node sound_prefs "Sound Preferences"

@{b}Game Music@{ub}

Turn the 'Game Music' on or off.

@{b}Highscore Music@{ub}

The  'Highscore Music' is played only if a new player gets into the highscore
list.

@{b}Sound FX@{ub}

The 'Sound FX' are all used while you play a game.

@endnode


@node network_prefs "Network Preferences"

@{b}@{u}Nullmodem:@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Device@{ub}

You  can select the device which should be used. The default is serial.device
and   works   on   every   Amiga   (other  successfully  tested  devices  are
BaudBandit.device and artser.device).

@{b}Unit@{ub}

Here you can select the unit that should be used.

@{b}Baud@{ub}

You can change the baudrate to the following values:

	300,600,1200,2400,4800,7200,9600,19200,38400,57600,115200

@{b}Transfer Mode@{ub}

Here you can select between a normal and a high speed mode. The difference is
that if you select "High Speed" no checksums are calculated and therefore the
amount  of  data  is  much  smaller.  If  you encounter any problems with the
nullmodem connection you should set this gadget to "Normal".

Important: the setting must be equal on both computers!


@{b}@{u}Modem:@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Device@{ub}

see Nullmodem

@{b}Unit@{ub}

see Nullmodem

@{b}Baud@{ub}

see Nullmodem

@{b}Init@{ub}

This string is used to initialize the modem. Sometimes it has to be changed.

@{b}Dial@{ub}

This string is used to dial a number. Sometimes is has to be changed.

@{b}Hangup@{ub}

This string is used to hang up. Sometimes is has to be changed.

@{b}Phone#1-4@{ub}

Here  you can enter four telephon number from which you can select one in the
network window.


@{b}@{u}TCP/IP:@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}AmiTCP/AS225@{ub}

Here you can switch between AmiTCP and AS225.

@{b}Host#1-4@{ub}

Here  you  can  enter  four hosts from wich you can select one in the network
window. It is possible to use both addresses (like a3000.nowhere.else) and IP
numbers!


@{b}@{u}Parnet:@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Local Path@{ub}

Here you can enter the local path where BattleDuel will create the files that
are needed for a Parnet/Pronet connection.

@{b}Remote Path@{ub}

Here you can enter the remote path where BattleDuel will create the files that
are needed for a Parnet/Pronet connection.



@{b}Type@{ub}

If  you want to establish a connection, one computer has to be the server and
the other one the client! This is very important and should be checked first.

@{b}RTS/CTS@{ub}

With  this  gadget  you  can select between hardware- and software-handshake.
Normally  you  should  enable  this  gadget,  but if you have problems with a
connection you can disable it.

@{b}Timeout@{ub}

Here  you  can enter the amount of seconds after which a timeout is detected.
If there are timeouts while you are doing a network game, it is recommendable
